{"title_page": "Sphenomegacorona", "text_new": "{{Infobox polyhedron\n| image         = sphenomegacorona.png\n| type          = [[Johnson solid|Johnson]]<br>[[augmented sphenocorona|J<sub>87</sub>]] - '''J<sub>88</sub>''' - [[hebesphenomegacorona|J<sub>89</sub>]]\n| faces         = 16 [[triangle]]s<br>2 [[square (geometry)|square]]s\n| edges         = 28\n| vertices      = 12\n| symmetry      = ''C''<sub>2v</sub>\n| vertex_config = 2(3<sup>4</sup>) <br> 2(3<sup>2</sup>.4<sup>2</sup>) <br> 2x2(3<sup>5</sup>) <br> 4(3<sup>4</sup>.4)\n| dual          = -\n| properties    = [[convex set|convex]]\n| net           = Johnson solid 88 net.png\n}}\n[[File:J88 sphenomegacorona.stl|thumb|3D model of a sphenomegacorona]]\nIn [[geometry]], the '''sphenomegacorona''' is one of the\n[[Johnson solid]]s (''J''<sub>88</sub>).\nIt is one of the elementary Johnson solids that do not arise from \"cut and paste\" manipulations of the [[Platonic solid|Platonic]] and [[Archimedean solid|Archimedean]] solids.\n\n{{Johnson solid|noref}}<ref name=\":0\">{{citation|last=Johnson|first=Norman W.|title=Convex polyhedra with regular faces|journal=[[Canadian Journal of Mathematics]]|volume=18|pages=169\u2013200|year=1966|doi=10.4153/cjm-1966-021-8|mr=0185507|zbl=0132.14603|author-link=Norman Johnson (mathematician)}}.</ref>\n\nJohnson uses the prefix ''spheno-'' to refer to a wedge-like complex formed by two adjacent ''lunes'', a lune being a [[square]] with [[Equilateral triangle|equilateral triangles]] attached on opposite sides. Likewise, the suffix ''-megacorona'' refers to a crownlike complex of 12 triangles. Joining both complexes together results in the sphenomegacorona.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Cartesian coordinates ==\nLet ''k'' \u2248 0.59463 be the smallest positive root of the [[polynomial]]\n\n:<math>1680 x^{16}- 4800 x^{15} - 3712 x^{14} + 17216 x^{13}+ 1568 x^{12} - 24576 x^{11}  + 2464 x^{10} + 17248 x^9 </math>\n:<math>{}-3384 x^8 - 5584 x^7 + 2000 x^6+ 240 x^5- 776 x^4+ 304 x^3 + 200 x^2 - 56 x -23.</math>\n\nThen, [[Cartesian coordinate system|Cartesian coordinates]] of a sphenomegacorona with edge length 2 are given by the union of the orbits of the points\n\n:<math>(0,1,2\\sqrt{1-k^2}),\\,(2k,1,0),\\,\\left(0,\\frac{\\sqrt{3-4k^2}}{\\sqrt{1-k^2}}+1,\\frac{1-2k^2}{\\sqrt{1-k^2}}\\right),</math>\n:<math>(1,0,-\\sqrt{2+4k-4k^2}),\\,\\left(0,\\frac{\\sqrt{3-4k^2}(2k^2-1)}{(k^2-1)\\sqrt{1-k^2}}+1,\\frac{2k^4-1}{(1-k^2)^{\\frac{3}{2}}}\\right)</math>\n\nunder the action of the [[Symmetry group|group]] generated by reflections about the xz-plane and the yz-plane.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Timofeenko|first=A. V.|date=2009|title=The non-Platonic and non-Archimedean noncomposite polyhedra|url=|journal=Journal of Mathematical Science|volume=162|issue=5|pages=720|via=}}</ref>\n\nWe may then calculate the [[surface area]] of a sphenomegacorona of edge length ''a'' as\n\n: <math>A=(2+4\\sqrt{3})a^2\\approx8.92820a^2.</math><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wolfram Research, Inc.|first=|date=2020|title=Wolfram{{!}}Alpha Knowledgebase|url=|journal=|location=Champaign, IL|volume=|pages=|quote=<code>PolyhedronData[{\"Johnson\", 88}, \"SurfaceArea\"]</code>|via=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{Mathworld2 | urlname2 = JohnsonSolid | title2 = Johnson solid | urlname =Sphenomegacorona| title = Sphenomegacorona }}\n\n[[Category:Johnson solids]]\n{{Johnson solids navigator}}\n{{Polyhedron-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox polyhedron\n| image         = sphenomegacorona.png\n| type          = [[Johnson solid|Johnson]]<br>[[augmented sphenocorona|J<sub>87</sub>]] - '''J<sub>88</sub>''' - [[hebesphenomegacorona|J<sub>89</sub>]]\n| faces         = 16 [[triangle]]s<br>2 [[square (geometry)|square]]s\n| edges         = 28\n| vertices      = 12\n| symmetry      = ''C''<sub>2v</sub>\n| vertex_config = 2(3<sup>4</sup>) <br> 2(3<sup>2</sup>.4<sup>2</sup>) <br> 2x2(3<sup>5</sup>) <br> 4(3<sup>4</sup>.4)\n| dual          = -\n| properties    = [[convex set|convex]]\n| net           = Johnson solid 88 net.png\n}}\n[[File:J88 sphenomegacorona.stl|thumb|3D model of a sphenomegacorona]]\nIn [[geometry]], the '''sphenomegacorona''' is one of the\n[[Johnson solid]]s (''J''<sub>88</sub>).\nIt is one of the elementary Johnson solids that do not arise from \"cut and paste\" manipulations of the [[Platonic solid|Platonic]] and [[Archimedean solid|Archimedean]] solids.\n\n{{Johnson solid|noref}}<ref name=\":0\">{{citation|last=Johnson|first=Norman W.|title=Convex polyhedra with regular faces|journal=[[Canadian Journal of Mathematics]]|volume=18|pages=169\u2013200|year=1966|doi=10.4153/cjm-1966-021-8|mr=0185507|zbl=0132.14603|author-link=Norman Johnson (mathematician)}}.</ref>\n\nJohnson uses the prefix ''spheno-'' to refer to a wedge-like complex formed by two adjacent ''lunes'', a lune being a [[square]] with [[Equilateral triangle|equilateral triangles]] attached on opposite sides. Likewise, the suffix ''-megacorona'' refers to a crownlike complex of 12 triangles. Joining both complexes together results in the sphenomegacorona.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Cartesian coordinates ==\nLet ''k'' \u2248 0.59463 be the smallest positive root of the [[polynomial]]\n\n:<math>1680 x^{16}- 4800 x^{15} - 3712 x^{14} + 17216 x^{13}+ 1568 x^{12} - 24576 x^{11}  + 2464 x^{10} + 17248 x^9 </math>\n:<math>- 3384 x^8 - 5584 x^7 + 2000 x^6+ 240 x^5- 776 x^4+ 304 x^3 + 200 x^2 - 56 x -23.</math>\n\nThen, [[Cartesian coordinate system|Cartesian coordinates]] of a sphenomegacorona with edge length 2 are given by the union of the orbits of the points\n\n:<math>(0,1,2\\sqrt{1-k^2}),\\,(2k,1,0),\\,\\left(0,\\frac{\\sqrt{3-4k^2}}{\\sqrt{1-k^2}}+1,\\frac{1-2k^2}{\\sqrt{1-k^2}}\\right),</math>\n:<math>(1,0,-\\sqrt{2+4k-4k^2}),\\,\\left(0,\\frac{\\sqrt{3-4k^2}(2k^2-1)}{(k^2-1)\\sqrt{1-k^2}}+1,\\frac{2k^4-1}{(1-k^2)^{\\frac{3}{2}}}\\right)</math>\n\nunder the action of the [[Symmetry group|group]] generated by reflections about the xz-plane and the yz-plane.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Timofeenko|first=A. V.|date=2009|title=The non-Platonic and non-Archimedean noncomposite polyhedra|url=|journal=Journal of Mathematical Science|volume=162|issue=5|pages=720|via=}}</ref>\n\nWe may then calculate the [[surface area]] of a sphenomegacorona of edge length ''a'' as\n\n: <math>A=(2+4\\sqrt{3})a^2\\approx8.92820a^2.</math><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wolfram Research, Inc.|first=|date=2020|title=Wolfram{{!}}Alpha Knowledgebase|url=|journal=|location=Champaign, IL|volume=|pages=|quote=<code>PolyhedronData[{\"Johnson\", 88}, \"SurfaceArea\"]</code>|via=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{Mathworld2 | urlname2 = JohnsonSolid | title2 = Johnson solid | urlname =Sphenomegacorona| title = Sphenomegacorona }}\n\n[[Category:Johnson solids]]\n{{Johnson solids navigator}}\n{{Polyhedron-stub}}\n", "name_user": "OfficialURL", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphenomegacorona"}
{"title_page": "2017 Boise State Broncos football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n|mode=football\n|year=2017\n|team=Boise State Broncos\n|image=Boise State \"B\" logo.svg\n|logo_size=150\n|conference=Mountain West Conference\n|division=Mountain Division\n|short_conf=MW\n|CoachRank=22\n|APRank=22\n|CFPRank=\n|record=11\u20133\n|conf_record=7\u20131\n|head_coach=[[Bryan Harsin]]\n|hc_year=4th\n|off_coach=Zak Hill\n|oc_year=2nd\n|off_scheme=[[Multiple offense|Multiple]]\n|def_coach=Andy Avalos\n|dc_year=2nd\n|def_scheme=Multiple\n|stadium=[[Albertsons Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 36,387)\n|champion=Mountain West champion<br>MW Mountain Division champion<br />Las Vegas Bowl champion\n|conf_champ=[[2017 Mountain West Conference Football Championship Game|MW Championship Game]]\n|conf_champ_result=W 17\u201314 vs. [[2017 Fresno State Bulldogs football team|Fresno State]]\n|bowl= [[2017 Las Vegas Bowl|Las Vegas Bowl]]\n|bowl_result= W 38\u201328 vs. [[2017 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon]]\n}}\n{{2017 Mountain West Conference football standings}}\nThe '''2017 Boise State Broncos football team''' represented [[Boise State University]] during the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. This season was the Broncos' 81st season overall, seventh as a member of the [[Mountain West Conference]] and fifth within the Mountain Division. The Broncos played their home games at [[Albertsons Stadium]] in [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]], [[Idaho]]. They were led by fourth-year head coach [[Bryan Harsin]]. They finished the season 11\u20133, 7\u20131 in Mountain West play to win the Mountain Division. They defeated West Division champion [[2017 Fresno State Bulldogs football team|Fresno State]] in the [[2017 Mountain West Conference Football Championship Game|Mountain West Championship Game]] to become Mountain West champions. They were invited to the [[2017 Las Vegas Bowl|Las Vegas Bowl]] where they defeated [[2017 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon]].\n\n==Preseason==\n===Award watch lists===\nListed in the order that they were released.\n\n'''[[Rimington Trophy]]''' \u2013 Sr. C Mason Hampton<ref>{{cite web|title=Rimington Trophy Press Release|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bosu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/misc_non_event/2017RimingtonSpringList.pdf|date=May 22, 2017|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Chuck Bednarik Award]]''' \u2013 Jr. DT David Moa<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Bednarik Award Watch List|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bosu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2017-18/misc_non_event/2017_Bednarik_Award_Watch_List.pdf|date=July 10, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Maxwell Award]]''' \u2013 Jr. QB [[Brett Rypien]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Maxwell Award Watch List|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bosu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2017-18/misc_non_event/2017_Maxwell_Award_Watch_List.pdf|date=July 10, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]]''' \u2013 Jr. DT David Moa<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 Bronko Nagurski Trophy watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-13/college-football-2017-bronko-nagurski-trophy-watch-list|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Outland Trophy]]''' \u2013 Sr. OT Archie Lewis & Jr. DT David Moa<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 OUTLAND TROPHY WATCH LIST UNVEILED|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bosu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2017-18/misc_non_event/2017_outland_trophy_preseason.pdf|date=July 13, 2017|accessdate=July 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[John Mackey Award]]''' \u2013 Sr. TE Jake Roh<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 John Mackey Award watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-11/college-football-2017-john-mackey-award-watch-list|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Paul Hornung Award]]''' \u2013 Sr. WR Cedrick Wilson<ref>{{cite web|titl