{"title_page": "Heinrich Kubis", "text_new": "'''Heinrich Kubis''' (16 June 1888 - 1979) was a German professional waiter known for serving as the world's first [[flight attendant]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thesocietypages.org/socimages/2013/07/23/before-the-stewardess-the-steward-when-flight-attendants-were-men/|title=Before the Stewardess, the Steward: When Flight Attendants Were Men|last=Wade|first=Lisa|date=23 July 2013|website=thesocietypages.org|publisher= |access-date=12 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> and for surviving the [[Hindenburg disaster]].\n\n==Career==\n\nKubis trained as a waiter and worked in several luxury hotels in Europe, including the [[H\u00f4tel Ritz Paris]] and the [[Carlton Hotel, London]].<ref name=Aerotime>{{cite web|url=https://www.aerotime.aero/aerotime.extra/23044-heinrich-kubus-first-flight-attendant|title=Heinrich Kubis: The First Flight Attendant|date=25 November 2016|website=Aerotime Hub|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> He survived the destruction of the ''Schwaben'' near [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] on 28 June 1912. \n\nIn March 1912 Kubis began attending to passengers on the [[LZ 10 Schwaben]] during flights from Berlin to Freidrichshafen.<ref>{{cite book|last=Law|first=Colin|date=2019|title=A Flight Attendant's Essential Guide: From Passenger Relations to Challenging Situations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_ecDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&dq=%22heinrich+kubis%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiaiO_EqOPoAhU0mHIEHTXfACMQ6AEwAXoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=%22heinrich%20kubis%22&f=false |publisher=BrownWalker Press|page=2|isbn=1627347283}}</ref> He thereby preceded the debut of the first female flight attendant, [[Ellen Church]], by eighteen years.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/05/may-15-1930-the-skies-get-a-little-bit-friendlier/ |title=May 15, 1930: The Skies Get a Little Bit Friendlier |author=Tony Long |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] magazine |date=May 15, 2008 |accessdate=August 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nKubis was on the ''[[LZ 129 Hindenburg|Hindeburg]]'' at the time of its [[Hindenburg disaster|destruction]] in New Jersey in 1937. On the ''Hindenburg'' Kubis was not only a flight attendant but the manager of the entire waitstaff, overseeing fifteen cooks and waiters.<ref>{{cite book |last=Foss|first=Richard|author-link= |date=11 December 2014|title=Food in the Air and Space: The Surprising History of Food and Drink in the Skies|url= |location= |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|page= |isbn=9781442227286}}</ref> He was responsible for confiscating cigarette lighters and matches from passengers as they boarded the aircraft, stating, \"We German don't fool around with hydrogen.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Perkes|first=Dan|author-link= |date=1976|title=Eyewitness to Disaster|url= |location= |publisher=Hammond|page=46|isbn=}} </ref> Kubis had nearly missed the voyage due to illness,<ref name=Aerotime></ref> but recovered in time to make the flight on 3 May. Kubis was in the dining room at the moment of the explosion, and helped passengers to jump to safety. He himself escaped the disaster without injury.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nielsen|first=Thor|author-link= |date=1955|title=The Zeppelin Story: The Life of Hugo Eckener|url= |location= |publisher= |page=227|isbn=}}</ref>\n\nHe died in 1979.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.globaltrainingaviation.com/en/blog/first-flight-attendant-history |title=First Flight Attendant in History|last= |first= |date=6 August 2020|website=Global Training Aviation|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\nKubis has figured in fictional works about the ''Hindeburg'' disaster: ''The Hindeburg Murders'' by Max Allan Collins (2000),<ref>{{cite book |last=Collins|first=Max Allan|author-link= |date=2000|title=The Hindenburg Murders|url= |location= |publisher=Berkley Prime Crime|page=39|isbn=0425174093}}</ref> and ''Flight of Dreams'' by Ariel Lawhon (2016).<ref>{{cite book |last=Lawhon|first=Ariel |author-link= |date=23 February 2016|title=Flight of Dreams: A Novel|url= |location= |publisher=Knopf Doubleday|page= |isbn=}} </ref> In the film ''[[Hindenburg: The Untold Story]]'' he was portrayed by actor [[Thorston Manderlay]]. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kubis, Heinrich}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:Flight attendants]]\n[[Category:German aviation record holders]]\n[[Category:LZ 129 Hindenburg]]\n", "text_old": "'''Heinrich Kubis''' (16 June 1888 - 1979) was a German professional waiter known for serving as the world's first [[flight attendant]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thesocietypages.org/socimages/2013/07/23/before-the-stewardess-the-steward-when-flight-attendants-were-men/|title=Before the Stewardess, the Steward: When Flight Attendants Were Men|last=Wade|first=Lisa|date=23 July 2013|website=thesocietypages.org|publisher= |access-date=12 April 2020|quote=}}</ref> and for surviving the [[Hindenburg disaster]].\n\n==Career==\n\nKubis trained as a waiter and worked in several luxury hotels in Europe, including the [[H\u00f4tel Ritz Paris]] and the [[Carlton Hotel, London]].<ref name=Aerotime>{{cite web|url=https://www.aerotime.aero/aerotime.extra/23044-heinrich-kubus-first-flight-attendant|title=Heinrich Kubis: The First Flight Attendant|date=25 November 2016|website=Aerotime Hub|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> He survived the destruction of the ''Schwaben'' near [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] on 28 June 1912. \n\nIn March 1912 Kubis began attending to passengers on the [[LZ 10 Schwaben]] during flights from Berlin to Freidrichshafen.<ref>{{cite book|last=Law|first=Colin|date=2019|title=A Flight Attendant's Essential Guide: From Passenger Relations to Challenging Situations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_ecDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&dq=%22heinrich+kubis%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiaiO_EqOPoAhU0mHIEHTXfACMQ6AEwAXoECAIQAg#v=onepage&q=%22heinrich%20kubis%22&f=false |publisher=BrownWalker Press|page=2|isbn=1627347283}}</ref> He thereby preceded the debut of the first female flight attendant, [[Ellen Church]], by eighteen years.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/05/may-15-1930-the-skies-get-a-little-bit-friendlier/ |title=May 15, 1930: The Skies Get a Little Bit Friendlier |author=Tony Long |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] magazine |date=May 15, 2008 |accessdate=August 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nKubis was on the ''[[LZ 129 Hindenburg|Hindeburg]]'' at the time of its [[Hindenburg disaster|destruction]] in New Jersey in 1937. On the ''Indenburg'' Kubis was not only a flight attendant but the manager of the entire waitstaff, overseeing fifteen cooks and waiters.<ref>{{cite book |last=Foss|first=Richard|author-link= |date=11 December 2014|title=Food in the Air and Space: The Surprising History of Food and Drink in the Skies|url= |location= |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|page= |isbn=9781442227286}}</ref> He was responsible for confiscating cigarette lighters and matches from passengers as they boarded the aircraft, stating, \"We German don't fool around with hydrogen.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Perkes|first=Dan|author-link= |date=1976|title=Eyewitness to Disaster|url= |location= |publisher=Hammond|page=46|isbn=}} </ref> Kubis had nearly missed the voyage due to illness,<ref name=Aerotime></ref> but recovered in time to make the flight on 3 May. Kubis was in the dining room at the moment of the explosion, and helped passengers to jump to safety. He himself escaped the disaster without injury.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nielsen|first=Thor|author-link= |date=1955|title=The Zeppelin Story: The Life of Hugo Eckener|url= |location= |publisher= |page=227|isbn=}}</ref>\n\nHe died in 1979.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.globaltrainingaviation.com/en/blog/first-flight-attendant-history |title=First Flight Attendant in History|last= |first= |date=6 August 2020|website=Global Training Aviation|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n\nKubis has figured in fictional works about the ''Hindeburg'' disaster: ''The Hindeburg Murders'' by Max Allan Collins (2000),<ref>{{cite book |last=Collins|first=Max Allan|author-link= |date=2000|title=The Hindenburg Murders|url= |location= |publisher=Berkley Prime Crime|page=39|isbn=0425174093}}</ref> and ''Flight of Dreams'' by Ariel Lawhon (2016).<ref>{{cite book |last=Lawhon|first=Ariel |author-link= |date=23 February 2016|title=Flight of Dreams: A Novel|url= |location= |publisher=Knopf Doubleday|page= |isbn=}} </ref> In the film ''[[Hindenburg: The Untold Story]]'' he was portrayed by actor [[Thorston Manderlay]]. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kubis, Heinrich}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:Flight attendants]]\n[[Category:German aviation record holders]]\n[[Category:LZ 129 Hindenburg]]\n", "name_user": "Lantzy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heinrich_Kubis"}
